commitResults.messageBody:
The NameContainsKeywordsPredicate class is used as a filter predicate in the `find` command's execution.
The class only supports filtering by case-insensitive word matching.

Let's integrate fuzzy search into the `find` command by adding support for fuzzy search in the NameContainsKeywordPredicate::test method. To accomplish this, let's add a method for fuzzy word matching in the StringUtil class, StringUtil::fuzzyMatch and its helper method String Util::levenshteinDistance.

We accomplish fuzzy string matching by computing the Levenshtein distance between two strings.
In order to add a new person info panel on the UI, let's decrease the width of the person list panel by decreasing the width of the PersonListPanel and making space for the new panel to be added.

The PersonListPanel width has been adjusted, but the PersonInfoPanel is missing from the UI.

Let's add the PersonListPanel class and its respective fxml file, and add it to the MainWindow.
A new style-class for data type heading text has been added to DarkTheme.css for the new panel.

In lieu of the new changes, there are checkStyle violations in the new/changed code.

Let's fix these violations in the MainWindow.java class and in PersonInfoPanel class.

Checkstyle violations in PersonInfoPanel.java were handled by adding appropriate JavaDoc comments.

commitResults.messageBody:
The tags displayed on the statistics dashboard did not follow the UI convention due to its style being hardcoded.
Additionally, the code for the Statistics dashboard has the FXMl and styles all defined in the Java class/controller.

Resolving the tag issue is necessary to keep the UI consistent. Additionally, the FXML style and node code being in the class
violates separation of concerns.

Lets resolve the tag issue and improve quality of code by refactoring the FXML component and design code into its FXML file.
